1. Brand Consistency & Professionalism the Good: 
Your LinkedIn is well-structured with a professional headshot and a clear headline highlighting your Integrated M.Tech at VIT Bhopal.
The Improvement: Your GitHub and Kaggle profiles currently use an "8-bit" avatar and a goose illustration, respectively. 
While creative, as you move into the security industry—which values trust and identity—consider using your LinkedIn headshot across all platforms to create a unified personal brand.
Bio Alignment: Your GitHub bio is very detailed (great for recruiters), but your Kaggle bio is empty ("No bio yet...").
Even a one-sentence hook on Kaggle, like "Exploring the intersection of Data Science and Cybersecurity" would help.

2. Technical Narrative GitHub: Your README is excellent. It clearly states your goals and tools (C++, Canva, Git). However, "Canva" and "Google Workspace" are listed under technologies. 
To a technical recruiter, these can distract from your core coding skills. 
Consider separating "Core Technologies" (C++, Python) from "Design & Productivity.
"Kaggle: You’ve already engaged with a "Malicious URLs dataset." 
This is a fantastic "bridge" project that connects Data Science to your Cyber Security major.

LinkedIn Activity: 
You are already posting content (the "Stay Alert, Stay Secure" post). 
This is the best way to build authority early.

3. Gap Analysis Skills Section: 
On LinkedIn, your top skills listed are "Pandas" and "Python." On GitHub, you emphasise "C++."

The Reflection: 
Ensure your "Top Skills" on LinkedIn match the "Tools I'm Exploring" on GitHub. 
Python and Pandas are your strongest allies.

Summary Table: 
Profile Status Platform Strength Area for Growth: LinkedIn. High engagement & clear academic path.
Needs a personalised Summary/About section.
GitHub: Well-organised README and contact info.
Needs more active repositories to back up the "Coder" username.
Kaggle: Good initial interest in security datasets.
Needs a bio and profile completion to look "active."
